'''Maria Popova''' is a Bulgarian writer, blogger, and critic living in [[Brooklyn]], New York.<ref name="NYT"/> She is perhaps most widely known for her [[blog]] BrainPickings.org, which features her writing on culture and [[found object]]s off and on the Internet.

== Education==
Popova graduated from an American high school in [[Bulgaria]]. In 2005, while studying at the [[University of Pennsylvania]] and working part-time at an advertising firm, she started an e-mail newsletter, intended to stir the creativity of her coworkers; they began forwarding it to others.<ref name="NYT">{{cite news | url=http://www.nytimes.com/2012/12/02/fashion/maria-popova-has-some-big-ideas.html?pagewanted=all | title=She's Got Some Big Ideas | work=The New York Times | date= November 30, 2012 | accessdate=December 01, 2012 | last=Feiler | first=Bruce}}</ref> Though her grandmother wanted her to get an [[MBA]], she graduated with a degree in Communications.<ref name= "MotherJones">{{cite web | url=http://www.motherjones.com/media/2011/12/maria-popova-interview | title=Maria Popova's Beautiful Mind | publisher=Mother Jones and the Foundation for National Progress | work=Mother Jones | date=January 2012 | accessdate=2012-12-01 | last=Levintova | first=Hannah}}</ref>

==Work==
{{rquote|right|If something interests me and is both timeless and timely, I write about it. Much of what is published online is content designed to be dead within hours, so I find most of my material [[offline]]. I gravitate more and more towards historical things that are somewhat obscure and yet timely in their sensibility and message.|Popova in December 2012<ref name="obs2012"/>}}
Popova's blog covers a wide variety of cultural topics: history, current events, and images and texts from the past.<ref name="MotherJones"/> The blog receives 1.2 million visitors a month,<ref name="obs2012"> {{cite web| url= http://www.guardian.co.uk/theobserver/2012/dec/30/maria-popova-brain-pickings-internet |title=Maria Popova: why we need an antidote to the culture of Google | date=29 December 2012 |work=''[[The Observer]]| first=Kathy|last= Sweeney | accessdate=2013-01-09}}</ref> and is followed be people including [[William Gibson]], [[Josh Groban]], [[Drew Carey]], [[David Eagleman]], and [[Mia Farrow]].{{cn}} She maintains a newsletter with 180,000 subscribers, and a [[Twitter]] account with 263,000 followers, as of December 2012. [[Anne-Marie Slaughter]] describes Popova's blog as "'like walking into the Museum of Modern Art and having somebody give you a customized, guided tour.'"<ref name="NYT"/> 

Popova has also written for ''[[The Atlantic]]'', ''[[Wired UK]]'', ''[[Good Worldwide|GOOD Magazine]]'', and the [[Nieman Foundation for Journalism|Nieman Journalism Lab]].<ref name= "MotherJones"/> She is an editorial director at the higher education [[social network]] [[Lore (company)|Lore]],<ref name="Lifehacker">{{cite web | url=http://lifehacker.com/5942623/im-maria-popova-and-this-is-how-i-work | title=I'm Maria Popova and this is how I work | publisher=Gawker Media | work=Lifehacker.com | date=September 12, 2012 | accessdate=December 01, 2012 | author=Miller, Tessa}}</ref> as well as an [[MIT]] Futures of Entertainment Fellow.<ref name="Atlanticcontribs">{{cite web | url=http://www.theatlantic.com/maria-popova/# | title=Maria Popova| publisher=The Atlantic Monthly Group | work=The Atlantic | accessdate=December 01, 2012}}</ref>

In 2012, Popova was named among the 100 Most Creative People in Business by ''[[Fast Company (magazine)|Fast Company Magazine]]''.<ref name="Fastcompany">{{cite web | url= http://www.fastcompany.com/most-creative-people/2012/maria-popova | title=How to make the Internet more personal | publisher=Mansueto Ventures LLC. | work=FastCompany.com | accessdate=December 01, 2012 | last=Kaganskiy | first=Julia}}</ref>

